This rule describes a recommended, minimal Rill project layout to help teams stay organized and make automation predictable.

## Recommended top-level layout

- apis/ — API definitions
- sources/ — source declarations and ingestion configs (e.g. CSV, S3, Snowflake, etc.)
- models/ — SQL models and modular transformations
- metrics/ — metrics/definition files or metrics views
- dashboards/ — dashboard definitions and assets
- connectors/ — external connector code and config
- rill.yaml — project configuration
- .env — local environment values (not checked into git)

## Organizing models

- Group models by domain where useful (e.g. `models/sales/`, `models/customers/`).
- Use an index or README in a nested folder to explain domain-specific decisions.

## Example structure

```
.gitignore
rill.yaml
apis/
	api.yaml
connectors/
	clickhouse.yaml
sources/
	auction_data_raw.yaml
	bids_data_raw.yaml
models/
	auction.yaml
	bids.yaml
    users.sql
metrics/
	auction_metrics.yaml
	bids_metrics.yaml
dashboards/
	auction_metrics_explore.yaml
	bids_metrics_explore.yaml
	bids_canvas.yaml
```

## Notes

- Keep unrelated artifacts out of the repo root when possible; store infra/ops configs in a clear place.
- Keep developer-facing docs short and local (README in folders) so new contributors can ramp up quickly.
